"1432","1375":"1375","about 1432":"circa 1432","1408":"1408","1439":"1439","Blakemere, Herefordshire, England":"Blakemere, Herefordshire, England","Speldhurst, Kent, England":"Speldhurst, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Parham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Parham, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Orpington, London, England, United Kingdom":"Orpington, London, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Spelhurst Church, Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England":"Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England","Saint Mary the Virgin Church, Wortham, Mid Suffolk district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Wortham, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1408–1493":"1408–1493","1394–1440":"1394–1440","1434–1461":"1434–1461","1432–1462":"1432–1462","1370–1439":"1370–1439","1375–Female":"1375–Deceased","1440":"1440","1462":"1462","1461":"1461","1493":"1493","1394":"1394","1370":"1370","1434":"1434","1455":"1455","1432":"1432","1375":"1375","about 1432":"about 1432","1408":"1408","1439":"1439","Blakemere, Herefordshire, England":"Blakemere, Herefordshire, England","Speldhurst, Kent, England":"Speldhurst, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Parham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Parham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Orpington, London, England, United Kingdom":"Orpington, London, England, United Kingdom","Spelhurst Church, Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England":"Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England","Saint Mary the Virgin Church, Wortham, Mid Suffolk district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Wortham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Waller","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>waler</i>, <i>waliere</i>, <i>walour</i>, <i>waller</i> ‘builder of walls, mason’.","English: in Sussex, perhaps a topographic name for someone who lived by a prominent wall.","English: topographic name for someone who lived by a spring, stream, or man-made well, from Middle English <i>waller</i>, a derivative of Middle English <i>walle</i>, Old English <i>wælle</i>, <i>wælle</i>. It is a West Midlands dialect form of   Weller  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wallar","meanings":["English: variant of   Waller  ."]},{"name":"Weller","meanings":["English (Surrey, Sussex, and Kent): topographic name for someone who lived by a spring, stream, or man-made well, from Middle English <i>weller</i>, <i>willer</i>, an agent derivative of Middle English <i>welle</i> (in southern England) and <i>wille</i> (in south western England), from Old English <i>wella</i>, <i>well(e)</i>, <i>wiella</i>, <i>wielle</i>, <i>willa</i>, <i>wyll(a)</i>, <i>wylle</i>. This type of name, a topographic term + <i>-er</i>, is particularly typical of Sussex and its neigbouring counties.","English: occupational name for someone who casts metal or who boils salt, from Middle English <i>weller</i>, <i>willer</i>, a derivative with <i>-er</i> of Old English <i>wellan</i>, <i>wiellan</i> ‘to boil’. Compare 5 below.","North German: variant of   Welle  , cognate with 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Gulby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Gaulby in Leicestershire."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":47,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Y